  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering penalties can include significant fines and prison sentences. Specific penalties depend on the circumstances of the offense, but generally include:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 10-20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines, often hundreds of thousands of dollars\n- Potential asset forfeiture\n\n2. Additional Potential Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Difficulty obtaining future employment\n- Financial institution restrictions\n\nThe exact penalties can vary based on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific federal statute violated\n- Whether the offense involved international transactions\n- Prior criminal history\n\nProsecutions typically occur under statutes like:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money Laundering Control Act)\n- Bank Secrecy Act\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations (RICO) Act\n\nFor precise details about a specific situation, consulting a qualified legal professional would be recommended, as money laundering laws are complex and case-specific.",
